04362nam a22006495i 9780231551090DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021036733  a97802315510907 a10.7312/roth194942doi  a(DE-B1597)635319  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aF128.39 4aF128.39 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a974.7/1qLOC  aNR 91602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/130254:1 aRothschild, Nan A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuried Beneath the City :bAn Archaeological History of New York /cH. Arthur Bankoff, Jessica Striebel MacLean, Amanda Sutphin, Nan A. Rothschild. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b196 color figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Indigenous Peoples Before the City -- t2. Dutch Beginnings, 1624–1664 -- t3. The British Colonial City and the Nascent Republic, 1664–1800 -- t4. Growing Pains, 1800–1840 -- t5. Development of the Modern City, 1840–1898 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A: The New York City Landmarks and Historic Districts Discussed in the Book -- tAppendix B: Archaeological Sites Within New York City Discussed in the Book -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBits and pieces of the lives led long before the age of skyscrapers are scattered throughout New York City, found in backyards, construction sites, street beds, and parks. Indigenous tools used thousands of years ago; wine jugs from a seventeenth-century tavern; a teapot from Seneca Village, the nineteenth-century Black settlement displaced by Central Park; raspberry seeds sown in backyard Brooklyn gardens—these everyday objects are windows into the city’s forgotten history.Buried Beneath the City uses urban archaeology to retell the history of New York, from the deeper layers of the past to the topsoil of recent events. The book explores the ever-evolving city and the day-to-day world of its residents through artifacts, from the first traces of Indigenous societies more than ten thousand years ago to the detritus of Dutch and English colonization and through to the burgeoning city’s transformation into the modern metropolis. It demonstrates how the archaeological record often goes beyond written history by preserving mundane things—details of everyday life that are beneath the notice of the documentary record. These artifacts reveal the density, diversity, and creativity of a city perpetually tearing up its foundations to rebuild itself. Lavishly illustrated with images of objects excavated in the city, Buried Beneath the City is at once an archaeological history of New York City and an introduction to urban archaeology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aBankoff, H. Arthur, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSutphin, Amanda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/roth1949440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231551090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231551090/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK